RVV benchmark AX45MPV (AndeSim simulator)

The Andes AX45MPV is an in-order dual-issue core with support for an up to 1024-bit vector unit.
These benchmarks were run on the AndeSim near-cycle-accurate microarchitecture simulator with the default AX45MPV configuration of VLEN=DLEN=512. While the simulator is supposed to be close to the actual implementation, and does model the CPU pipeline and caches, there are definitely differences from running on the actual AX45MPV implementation.
Thanks to Andes for providing access to their tooling for the "RISC-V Hackathon Online" RVI event and allowing me to share these results.

  • Return to parent page

Based on this commit.

Benchmarks

  • memcpy
  • memset
  • strlen
  • utf8 count
  • merge escaped lines
  • mandelbrot
  • reverse byte order of 32 bit elements
  • 4-bit lookup table
  • 6-bit lookup table
  • histogram
  • ascii to utf16 (zero extend 1->2 bytes)
  • ascii to utf32 (zero extend 1->4 bytes)
  • chacha20
  • poly1305
  • base64 encode
  • veclibm

Instruction timings

The following are measured cycle averages when unrolling and looping over the given instruction, which should estimate the instruction throughput. The registers involved are randomized to usual values, that is floating point values are real numbers and not NaN/Inf, and instructions like vslide* stay within the vl range Some valid vtype-instruction combinations are missing.

Example measurement code for vadd.vx
LMUL=1LMUL=4
bench_vaddvx_m1:
m_nop
	li a0, WARMUP
1:
	vadd.vx v8,v16,t0
	vadd.vx v9,v17,t1
	vadd.vx v10,v18,t2
	vadd.vx v11,v19,t3
	vadd.vx v12,v20,t4
	vadd.vx v13,v21,t5
	vadd.vx v14,v22,t6
	vadd.vx v15,v23,t7
	addi a0, a0, -1
	bnez a0, 1b
	li a0, LOOP
	rdcycle a1
1:
.rept UNROLL
	vadd.vx v8,v16,t0
	vadd.vx v9,v17,t1
	vadd.vx v10,v18,t2
	vadd.vx v11,v19,t3
	vadd.vx v12,v20,t4
	vadd.vx v13,v21,t5
	vadd.vx v14,v22,t6
	vadd.vx v15,v23,t7
.endr
	addi a0, a0, -1
	bnez a0, 1b
	fence.i
	rdcycle a0
	sub a0, a0, a1
	ret
